// pseudo-track-commit.sh
// Records source files changed in the most recent git commit to .pseudo-needs-update so stale pseudo files can be identified and regenerated.
// synced: 2026-03-26T13:51:59Z

// Called by both the git post-commit hook and pseudo-hook-check.sh. Must be run from the project root or any subdirectory of the repo. Writes relative file paths to $PROJECT_ROOT/.pseudo-needs-update, appending to any existing content, then deduplicates and sorts in place.

FUNCTION pseudo-track-commit [2026-03-26]
  Step 1. Verify the current directory is inside a git repo; exit 0 silently if not.
  Step 2. Count commits reachable from HEAD. IF fewer than 2, exit 0 (no previous commit to diff against).
  Step 3. Resolve PROJECT_ROOT via `git rev-parse --show-toplevel`. Set MANIFEST to $PROJECT_ROOT/.pseudo-needs-update.
  Step 4. Run `git diff HEAD~1 HEAD --name-only --diff-filter=AMR` to get Added, Modified, and Renamed files from the last commit.
  Step 5. Filter results to only source file extensions: ts, tsx, js, jsx, mjs, py, go, rs, rb, java, swift, kt, c, cpp, h.
  Step 6. Exclude test files, __tests__ directories, node_modules, dist/, build/, and .d.ts declaration files.
  Step 7. Append surviving paths to MANIFEST. Errors are suppressed so the hook never blocks a commit.
  Step 8. IF MANIFEST exists and is non-empty, sort and deduplicate it in place with `sort -u`.
